display="inline"><![CDATA[f_{n}(x)=x^{n}]]></fr:tex>. By the <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0025.xml"
addr="ca-0025"
title="Heine-Cantor theorem">Heine-Cantor theorem</fr:link>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_{n}\}]]></fr:tex> is a countably infinite set of uniformly continuous functions on the closed interval <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[[0,1]]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>But this collection is not equicontinuous at <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x=1]]></fr:tex>. For a fixed <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\leq  x<1]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[|f_{n}(1)-f_{n}(x)|=1-x^{n}]]></fr:tex> and no matter how close to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex> we take <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{n}\to 0]]></fr:tex>, so there is an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1-x^{n}>\varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>. This means <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{f_{n}\}]]></fr:tex> is not equicontinuous.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
